{"serial": "12006", "department_serial": 13, "code": "EL1201", "class": "*", "name": {"en": "Comparative History of Ideas", "ch": "比較觀念文化史"}, "notice": {"en": "", "ch": ""}, "instructor": {"en": ["Claudio Sansone"], "ch": ["倉誦凝"]}, "credits": 3, "time_loc": [{"time": {"week": 5, "session": ["5", "6", "7"]}, "loc": {"building": "C2", "room": "101"}}], "isRequired": false, "isFullSem": false, "MaxStu": 50, "department": {"ch": "英美語文學系", "en": "Department of English"}, "system": {"ch": "學士班", "en": "Undergraduate Programme"}, "language": {"ch": "英語", "en": "English"}, "card": {"ch": "部份使用", "en": "Optional"}, "assigned": 1, "selected": 51, "remark": {"ch": "", "en": ""}, "goal": {"ch": "Comp History \n\nPoetry, Property, and Possession\n\n\n\nThis course introduces freshmen to the basic skills of critical thinking required in the study of English literature, cultural studies, and critical theory. It does so through a dialectic analysis of key concepts in Western thought. We will examine the assumptions and premises or major topics regarding the function of poetry in society, with an emphasis on notions of property, possession, and individualism. We will see that poetry occupies a space of radical resistance to the dominant ideologies of any time period. Students are expected to complete readings at home and to bring questions to class (graded course component). The course also introduces students to the basics of how to occupy a college classroom by challenging the instructor and how to engage in argumentative writing (graded course component).", "en": "Comp History \n\nPoetry, Property, and Possession\n\n\n\nThis course introduces freshmen to the basic skills of critical thinking required in the study of English literature, cultural studies, and critical theory. It does so through a dialectic analysis of key concepts in Western thought. We will examine the assumptions and premises or major topics regarding the function of poetry in society, with an emphasis on notions of property, possession, and individualism. We will see that poetry occupies a space of radical resistance to the dominant ideologies of any time period. Students are expected to complete readings at home and to bring questions to class (graded course component). The course also introduces students to the basics of how to occupy a college classroom by challenging the instructor and how to engage in argumentative writing (graded course component)."}, "outline": {"ch": "At the heart of this experiment and theory and the history of ideas, we will engage with the seeming “inevitability” of contemporary global capitalism. We will question whether notions of labor, alienation, progress, inequality, freedom, and others are as obvious and necessary as they seem.", "en": "At the heart of this experiment and theory and the history of ideas, we will engage with the seeming “inevitability” of contemporary global capitalism. We will question whether notions of labor, alienation, progress, inequality, freedom, and others are as obvious and necessary as they seem."}, "textbook": {"ch": "ee-class", "en": "ee-class"}, "selfCompiledRate": {"ch": "0", "en": "0"}, "instructMethod": {"ch": "講授\n研討", "en": ["Lecture", "Seminar"]}, "gradMethod": {"ch": "Students must attend class having completed the readings. Students must bring questions on card to class each week. This weekly activity, as well as student participation in discussion, will amount to 30％ of the class grade. A further 20％ will be determined by group presentations that will be spread out across the semester, in which groups of students will lead discussion on key topics in our readings. Another 20％ will be determined through an in-class midterm exam, through which students will be asked to define and identify several key terms discussed in the first half of the course, and to compose a very short essay (500 words). The final 30％ of the class will be determined through a final paper of 4-5 pages (double spaced, 12-point Times New Roman), which students will write by building on one of several provided essay topics or by determining their own topic with the Professor’s assistance.", "en": "Students must attend class having completed the readings. Students must bring questions on card to class each week. This weekly activity, as well as student participation in discussion, will amount to 30％ of the class grade. A further 20％ will be determined by group presentations that will be spread out across the semester, in which groups of students will lead discussion on key topics in our readings. Another 20％ will be determined through an in-class midterm exam, through which students will be asked to define and identify several key terms discussed in the first half of the course, and to compose a very short essay (500 words). The final 30％ of the class will be determined through a final paper of 4-5 pages (double spaced, 12-point Times New Roman), which students will write by building on one of several provided essay topics or by determining their own topic with the Professor’s assistance."}, "officeHour": {"ch": "Fri 13:00 C2-423", "en": "Fri 13:00 C2-423"}, "teachWeeks": {"ch": "16+2", "en": "16+2"}, "flexDiscription": {"ch": "Preparations of Final Papers", "en": "Preparations of Final Papers"}, "domain": {"ch": "語言學與英語教學\n\n\n、\n\n\n文學\n\n\n、\n\n\n文化研究\n\n\n、\n\n\n文學與文化研究", "en": "語言學與英語教學\n\n\n、\n\n\n文學\n\n\n、\n\n\n文化研究\n\n\n、\n\n\n文學與文化研究"}, "map": {"ch": [{"competencies": "英文閱讀解析與寫作論述", "rating": "(5)非常高", "assesments": ["紙筆測驗/會考", "作業練習", "口頭報告/口試", "專題研究報告(書面)", "出席/課堂表現", "自我評量/同儕互評"]}, {"competencies": "英語溝通與文化跨越", "rating": "(5)非常高", "assesments": ["口頭報告/口試", "出席/課堂表現", "自我評量/同儕互評"]}, {"competencies": "審美欣賞與多元創意", "rating": "(5)非常高", "assesments": ["紙筆測驗/會考", "出席/課堂表現"]}, {"competencies": "人文思維與社會關懷", "rating": "(5)非常高", "assesments": ["紙筆測驗/會考", "實作/實驗", "出席/課堂表現"]}, {"competencies": "組織能力與人際合作", "rating": "(3)普通", "assesments": ["出席/課堂表現"]}], "en": [{"competencies": "English critica